👉 Hashing is a technique used to:

Store data quickly
Search data quickly
Access data using a key

Instead of searching element one by one, Java uses a hash function to directly find the location of data.

👉 Real Life Example

Imagine a library:
  Every book has a unique code
  Using that code, librarian directly finds the book location
That code system is similar to hashing.

👉 What is Hash Function?

A hash function converts data into a unique integer value called:
                                                                  Hash Code
Java uses this hash code to store data internally.

Formula Idea :
            Index = hashCode % Size
This index tells where data will be stored.

👉 Hashing in Java Collections

Java provides hashing through:
    HashMap
    HashSet
    Hashtable
These are part of the Java Collections Framework.

1. HashMap

Stores data in:
            Key → Value

Example :

import java.util.*;

public class HashMapDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        HashMap<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();

        map.put(1, "Rahul");
        map.put(2, "Aman");
        map.put(3, "Karan");

        System.out.println(map);

        System.out.println(map.get(2));

        map.remove(1);

        System.out.println(map);
    }
}

Output :

{1=Rahul, 2=Aman, 3=Karan}
Aman
{2=Aman, 3=Karan}

👉 Important Methods of HashMap

| Method          | Work               |
| --------------- | ------------------ |
| put()           | Insert data        |
| get()           | Access value       |
| remove()        | Delete element     |
| containsKey()   | Check key exists   |
| containsValue() | Check value exists |
| size()          | Returns size       |
| clear()         | Removes all data   |


2. HashSet

Used to store:
      Unique elements only
      No duplicate values

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class HashSetDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        set.add(10);
        set.add(20);
        set.add(10);

        System.out.println(set);
    }
}

OUTPUT : 

[10, 20]
Duplicate 10 is removed automatically.

👉 Collision in Hashing

Sometimes two values generate same hash code.

This problem is called: Collision

Java handles collisions using:
                            Linked List
                            Balanced Trees (in newer versions)

Internal Working of HashMap

Step 1 Key generates hash code
Step 2 Java calculates index.
Step 3 Data stored at that bucket/index.

Time Complexity

| Operation | Average Time |
| --------- | ------------ |
| Insert    | O(1)         |
| Search    | O(1)         |
| Delete    | O(1)         |

👉 Difference: HashMap vs Hashtable

| HashMap          | Hashtable       |
| ---------------- | --------------- |
| Not synchronized | Synchronized    |
| Faster           | Slower          |
| Allows null      | No null allowed |
| Modern           | Legacy class    |

👉 Difference: HashSet vs HashMap

| HashSet                 | HashMap                |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Stores only values      | Stores key-value pairs |
| No duplicates           | Keys unique            |
| Uses HashMap internally | Direct implementation  |
